<p>The critical issue here is that there=E2=80=99s no aggregate check to en=
sure <code>msg.value</code> covers both <code>genesisCircSupply</code> and =
<code>collateral</code>. Each <code>lock</code> call independently checks a=
gainst the same <code>msg.value</code>, allowing the same funds to be count=
ed twice.</p>
<p>This flaw breaks a critical invariant of the bridging protocol <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/code-423n4/2025-02-recall/tree/main#:~:text=3DThe%20=
total%20supply,within%20the%20subnet">=E2=80=9Cthe total supply of a subnet=
 must match the total funds locked for that subnet in the gateway=E2=80=9D<=
/a>.</p>
<p>This means a malicious actor could:</p>
<ol>
<li>Call <code>register</code> with <code>genesisCircSupply =3D X</code> an=
d <code>collateral =3D X</code>.</li>
<li>Send only <code>X</code> in <code>msg.value</code>.</li>
<li>Both lock calls would pass since <code>msg.value &gt;=3D X</code> for e=
ach.</li>
<li>The subnet would be registered with <code>X circulating supply</code> a=
nd <code>X collateral</code>, despite only <code>X</code> total funds being=
 provided.</li>
</ol>
